<section id="fs-idm538618736" class="review-problems"><title>Problems</title>
<exercise id="fs-idm1291686128">
<problem id="fs-id1165038975673">
<para id="fs-id1165038975675">Suppose you have a spectrometer that can measure wavelengths to a precision of 0.3%. What is the minimum speed at which a light source must travel toward you for you to be able to determine that its wavelength is Doppler shifted? That is, what speed produces a shift of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>0.300</m:mn><m:mtext>%</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math>?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1165039085747">
<para id="fs-id1165039085749">A measurable shift occurs when <m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mtext>Δ</m:mtext><m:mtext>λ</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mtext>λ</m:mtext></m:mfrac><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mi>c</m:mi></m:mfrac><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:mn>0.003</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math>; therefore <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0.003</m:mn><m:mi>c</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>9.0</m:mn><m:mo>x</m:mo><m:msup><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:msup><m:mtext>m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math></para></solution>
</exercise><exercise id="eip-845"><problem id="eip-516">
  <para id="eip-671">The spectral line in hydrogen that, in the laboratory, has a wavelength of 656.3 nm, is detected in the spectrum of a distant object at a wavelength of 657.0 nm. How fast is this object receding from Earth?
  </para></problem>

<solution id="eip-0">
  <para id="eip-291">v = 320 km/s
  </para></solution>
</exercise><exercise id="eip-238"><problem id="eip-782">
  <para id="eip-166">
   Light from distant nebulae contains radio-frequency radiation that originates in hydrogen atoms and has a wavelength of 21 cm. Suppose such a nebula is approaching Earth at a speed of 15,000 km/s. At what wavelength would our radio telescopes measure this radiation?
  </para>
</problem>

<solution id="eip-42">
  <para id="eip-390">
    20 cm
  </para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</section>
